### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

Not recently, but it was probably introduced in the last couple of years.

### Description

If an `@Injectable` has a `.name` property, and the name property throws, it causes an injection failure. This is due to brittle design in `isNotFound()` called in `injectInjectorOnly()`.

Here's a test that fails (the same behavior occurs outside of tests):
```ts
import { inject, Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { TestBed } from '@angular/core/testing';

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
class LoadableThing {
  public isLoaded = false;

  get name(): string {
    if (!this.isLoaded) {
      throw new Error('Not loaded');
    }
    return 'LoadedName';
  }
}

@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
class ServiceHost {
  readonly loadable = inject(LoadableThing);
}

describe('inject() function', () => {

  it('should not throw if the injected object has a `name` property that throws', () => {
    const host = TestBed.inject(ServiceHost);
    expect(host.loadable).toBeTruthy();
  });

});
```

If I comment out the `throw` line in `LoadableThing.name` injection (and the test) works as expected.

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

See test above

